LogFile.FinalText:
Hydroxyurea in sickel cell syndrome patients from the Hemope Hospital, Recife (State of Pernambuco), Brazil.
Sickle cell syndromes (SCS) form a set of qualitative hemoglobin diseases in which the hemoglobin S gene is inherited. [1] Among such syndromes, the most frequent is the sickel cell anemia (SS homozygosis), in which patients present organic demages since childhood resulting from repeated vascular-occlusive episodes. [2] Several studies with adults have demonstrated the efficacy of hydroxyurea (HU) use, of which main effect is the rise of fetal hemoglobin levels (FHb) among SCS pateints with little or no side effects. [3, 4, 5, 6]. HU is a well-known chemotherapy agent which is used in the treatment of myeloproliferative disorders such as chronic myeloid leukemia and polycythemia vera. Its main function is the blocking of DNA synthesis by inhibition of ribonucleotide reductase, keeping cells in S phase. [1] It is easy to use, with few toxic effects, and with reversed myelosuppressive effect. Hydroxyurea use in of sickle cell anemia treatment protocols started in the 1980s with adult patients. Its use with chlidren was later authorized. [7] Over the years, studies with children have demonstrated equal HU efficacy, without major side effects. [2, 7, 8, 9, 10]. The present study is thus aimed at investigating, after a series of cases, the efficacy and tolerability of HU use by patients with SCS at both pediatric age and early adulthood. It is also aimed at evaluating hematological parameter variations in both age groups, and FHb values in the pediatric age group.
